    <text>
        <body>
            <head>187. Telegram From the Department of State to the Embassy in Tunisia<note n="1"
                    place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d187fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59,
                    Central Foreign Policy File, D770050–0377. Confidential; Immediate. Drafted by
                        <persName corresp="recSv8kXhhqWsvvbj">Wilkinson</persName>; cleared in
                        <gloss target="#t_NEA_1">NEA</gloss> and S/S; approved by <persName
                        corresp="reclbVMhofbughnCg">Habib</persName>.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1977-02-12T00:19:00+00:00">February 12, 1977, 0019Z</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>32245. Subject: <persName corresp="reclbVMhofbughnCg">Habib</persName>-<persName
                    corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA">Hedda</persName> Meeting of February 11, 1977.</p>
            <p>1. In brief conversation with Under Secretary <persName corresp="reclbVMhofbughnCg"
                    >Habib</persName>, Ambassador <persName corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA"
                    >Hedda</persName> renewed request for <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rechzihAcwY5mmgLh">security supporting assistance</rs> for <placeName
                    corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName> and gave views on various
                options for exchanges of high-level visits.</p>
            <p>2. Recalling background of Foreign Minister <persName corresp="recJ2LgM5qsYgq9Dd"
                    >Chatty</persName>’s October meeting with Secretary <persName
                    corresp="rectUrMkOWahA6Bv8">Kissinger</persName>
                <note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d187fn2">See <ref target="frus1969-76ve09p1#d127">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1969–1976, vol. E–9,
                        Part 1, Documents on North Africa, 1973–1976, Document 127</ref>.</note> and
                subsequent discussions, <persName corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA">Hedda</persName> asked
                that new <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">administration</rs> consider
                extending <rs type="topic" corresp="rechzihAcwY5mmgLh">security supporting
                    assistance</rs> to <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName> to
                set example for others in region of potential rewards for close cooperation with
                    <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>. He said he had talked to Sens. <persName
                    corresp="recjsWF8n1J8RfL7y">Humphrey</persName> and <persName
                    corresp="recCCrWX2ZR2402Db">Percy</persName> and Cong. <persName
                    corresp="recYRXLDW3G09UBSB">Zablocki</persName> and found them receptive to
                idea. <persName corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA">Hedda</persName> also renewed request
                for “political” meeting with high <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> representative,
                to precede an early meeting of <orgName corresp="recHh5Ro1Ueoi84PG">Joint
                    Commission</orgName>.<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d187fn3">The <orgName
                        corresp="recHh5Ro1Ueoi84PG">U.S.-<placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj"
                            >Tunisian</placeName> Joint Commission</orgName> first met in Washington
                    in May 1975.</note>
            </p>
            <p>3. <persName corresp="reclbVMhofbughnCg">Habib</persName> asked if <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recfsYEHWUfhmWQY2">security assistance</rs> question would be an
                essential agenda item for <orgName corresp="recHh5Ro1Ueoi84PG">Joint
                    Commission</orgName>; <persName corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA">Hedda</persName>
                said no, question could best be decided independently. <persName
                    corresp="reclbVMhofbughnCg">Habib</persName> asked if next <orgName
                    corresp="recHh5Ro1Ueoi84PG">Joint Commission</orgName> meeting in Tunis could be
                chaired for <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> by someone other than Secretary
                    <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Vance</persName> in view of latter’s
                crowded travel schedule in next few months. <persName corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA"
                    >Hedda</persName> said it would be most desirable for the Secretary to attend
                    <orgName corresp="recHh5Ro1Ueoi84PG">Joint Commission</orgName>, perhaps at some
                point during his March Moscow trip, but he was sure <gloss target="#t_GOT_1">
                    <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">GOT</placeName>
                </gloss> would be pleased if <persName corresp="reclbVMhofbughnCg">Habib</persName>
                himself were to lead <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> delegation in place of
                Secretary. He reiterated <gloss target="#t_GOT_1">
                    <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">GOT</placeName>
                </gloss> appreciation for political/military support that <persName
                    corresp="reclbVMhofbughnCg">Habib</persName> had helped to organize during
                difficult days in August, 1976.<note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d187fn4">See <ref
                        target="frus1969-76ve09p1#d126">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1969–1976, vol. E–9,
                        Part 1, Documents on North Africa, 1973–1976, Document 126</ref>.</note>
            </p>
            <p>4. On the subject of a possible high-level <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj"
                    >Tunisian</placeName> visit to the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>, <persName
                    corresp="reclbVMhofbughnCg">Habib</persName> said we will have to look into
                question of visit by Prime Minister <persName corresp="rec8IOwPGGW4LB0wR"
                    >Nouira</persName>, since health appears to preclude visit by President
                    <persName corresp="recQM7EFz4UiiW2Xj">Bourguiba</persName>. However, he noted
                that there is an overwhelming number of requests <pb facs="0469" n="448"
                    xml:id="pg_448"/> for high-level visits. <persName corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA"
                    >Hedda</persName> recognized this difficulty, but asked that <gloss
                    target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> give first priority to its best friends. <persName
                    corresp="rec8IOwPGGW4LB0wR">Nouira</persName> would not want to make a State
                visit, just a brief working visit without fanfare which would take very little of
                President <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8">Carter</persName>’s time.</p>
            <p>5. <persName corresp="reclbVMhofbughnCg">Habib</persName> said we should plan firmly
                for a <orgName corresp="recHh5Ro1Ueoi84PG">Joint Commission</orgName> meeting, and
                that he would explore questions raised by <persName corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA"
                    >Hedda</persName> with Secretary <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu"
                    >Vance</persName> during trip next week, as well as with Ambassador <persName
                    corresp="recoYGZSMuqMPW41n">Mulcahy</persName> at scheduled Amman meeting. In
                conclusion, he briefed <persName corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA">Hedda</persName> on
                purely exploratory nature of the Secretary’s <placeName corresp="recJAi0OpNdSuYev5"
                    >Middle East</placeName> trip.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">Vance</hi>
                    </persName>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
